1. What is a static variable?
-->A static variable is a variable declared using the static keyword inside a class.
  👉 It belongs to the class, not to individual objects.
  class Demo {
      static int count = 0;
  }



2. How does a static variable differ from an instance variable?
-->
| Static Variable         | Instance Variable                    |
| ----------------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| Belongs to **class**    | Belongs to **object**                |
| Single copy shared      | Separate copy per object             |
| Loaded once in memory   | Created every time object is created |
| Access using class name | Access using object                  |



3. When and why do we use static variables?
-->👉 Use static variables when:
    You want to share data across all objects
    Value should be common for all instances
    Examples:
    Counter (number of objects created)
    Company name (same for all employees)


4. How many copies of a static variable exist in memory?
-->👉 Only ONE copy exists in memory.
  ✔ Shared by all objects of that class


5. Can a static variable be local to a method?
-->❌ No   
    👉 static variables:
    Must be declared inside class
    Cannot be declared inside a method
    void test() {
        // static int x = 10; ❌ Not allowed
    }


6. Can we access static variables without creating an object?
-->✅ Yes
    
    👉 Best practice:
    
    ClassName.variableName
    
    Example:
    
    class Demo {
        static int x = 10;
    }
    
    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            System.out.println(Demo.x);
        }
    }



7. What are some real-world examples of using static variables?
-->👉 Common use cases:
    Counter:
    class Test {
        static int count = 0;
    
        Test() {
            count++;
        }
    }
    Configuration values:
    Company name
    App version
    Constants (with final)
    static final double PI = 3.14;



8. What happens if two classes have static variables with the same name?
-->👉 No problem at all.
    ✔ They are completely independent
    class A {
        static int x = 10;
    }
    
    class B {
        static int x = 20;
    }
    
    👉 Access using:
    A.x  // 10
    B.x  // 20


9. Can we change the value of a static variable in another class?
-->✅ Yes (if not final)  
    👉 You can modify using class name:
    class A {
        static int x = 10;
    }
    
    class B {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            A.x = 50;
            System.out.println(A.x); // 50
        }
    }

10. Is it possible to make a static variable final?
-->✅ Yes

    👉 This creates a constant
    
    class Demo {
        static final int MAX = 100;
    }
    
    ✔ Value cannot be changed
    ✔ Commonly used for constants like:
    
    PI
    MAX_SIZE



-->✅ Final Interview Tip
👉 Say this confidently:
"Static variables are class-level variables shared across all objects, used to store common data and reduce memory usage."






Programs
1. Count the number of objects created using a static variable
-->👉 Idea: Use a static counter that increments in the constructor.
    class CounterDemo {
        static int count = 0;
    
        CounterDemo() {
            count++;
            System.out.println("Object created. Count = " + count);
        }
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            new CounterDemo();
            new CounterDemo();
            new CounterDemo();
    
            System.out.println("Total objects created: " + CounterDemo.count);
        }
    }
    ✅ Output:
    Object created. Count = 1
    Object created. Count = 2
    Object created. Count = 3
    Total objects created: 3



2. Demonstrate that static variables are shared between all objects.
-->👉 Idea: Change value from one object and show it reflects in others.
    class SharedDemo {
        static int x = 10;
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            SharedDemo obj1 = new SharedDemo();
            SharedDemo obj2 = new SharedDemo();
    
            obj1.x = 50;
    
            System.out.println("obj1.x = " + obj1.x);
            System.out.println("obj2.x = " + obj2.x);
        }
    }
    
    ✅ Output:
    obj1.x = 50
    obj2.x = 50
    
    👉 Shows: Same memory → shared value



3. Use a static variable for generating a unique ID for every object.
-->👉 Idea: Increment static variable and assign it to each object. 
    class Student {
        static int counter = 1000;
        int id;
    
        Student() {
            counter++;
            id = counter;
        }
    
        void display() {
            System.out.println("Student ID: " + id);
        }
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Student s1 = new Student();
            Student s2 = new Student();
            Student s3 = new Student();
    
            s1.display();
            s2.display();
            s3.display();
        }
    }
    
    ✅ Output:
    
    Student ID: 1001
    Student ID: 1002
    Student ID: 1003
